x4freetext: the electron beam hitting a rotating uranium target
Fast neutron from the target moderated to a
white spectrum by water contained in berillium
canning of 4.0cm thick walls situated below and above
background points were determined with black
resonance technique Na, Ge, S, Co, Bi. The background
was deduced from a fit of the background points with
a function like BKG=a+b*TOF**c with a, b and c free
parameters and TOF the neutron time-of-flight
placed at approx. 25 m from the neutron source.
The sample was positioned in and out of the beam
GELINA Flight path number 4; angle of the flight
path with respect to the electron beam is 261.degr,
.Neutrons detected with 0.5 cm thick slab of
sintered BC4, which was view by 4x(10cm x 5 cm)
C6D6 liquid scintillators perpendicular to the beam
at 48.2017 +/- 0.0012 m from the neutron source.
BF3 monitors were located above the neutron
.Flight path distance is fitted with REFIT, and
describes the distance between the face of the
moderator to the face of the detector. Two additional,
energy  dependent components have to be added to
account for the neutron distribution of the moderator
and the detector.The transmission factor is obtained
from dead time and background corrected yields
* Background based on S, Na, Ge, Co, Bi
SD: THICKNESS was added to Subent 002.
function of the energy. Averaged over energy interval
Data taken from S.Kopecky via INTERNET
